          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search          James Peterkin Alexander (June 28, 1835 – April 16, 1912[1]) was a Scottish-born farmer and political figure in Manitoba. He represented Turtle Mountain from 1881 to 1883 and Souris from 1886 to 1888 in the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as a Conservative. He was born in Edinburgh, the son of William Alexander, and was educated at the normal school and the University of Edinburgh. In 1872, he married Margaret Crawford. Alexander was a Glasgow merchant until 1878 when he was forced out of business by the failure of the City of Glasgow Bank. In November 1879, he emigrated to the Turtle Mountain area of southern Manitoba. Alexander was defeated when he ran for reelection in 1883. He was a magistrate and coroner for the province and served as registrar of deeds for Souris County from 1883 to 1886. He later was editor of the Deloraine Advertiser and registrar for the Boissevain land title office.[2] Alexander died in a barber's chair of a heart attack after hearing of his friend John Hugo Ross's death on the Titanic.[3] References[edit]   ^ "Genealogy Searches for Unrestricted Records". Government of Manitoba. Registration number 1912-002767. Retrieved 2012-09-29.  ^ "James Peterkin Alexander (1835-?)". Memorable Manitobans. Manitoba Historical Society. Retrieved 2012-09-29.  ^ "Titanic -- The Manitoba connection". Winnipeg Free Press. April 14, 2012. Retrieved 2012-09-29.        This article about a Manitoba politician is a stub. You can help Wikipedia by expanding it.   v t e                         Retrieved from "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=James_Peterkin_Alexander&oldid=722349641"          Categories: 1835 births1912 deathsProgressive Conservative Party of Manitoba MLAsManitoba politician stubsHidden categories: All stub articles            
